Mistakes : #1 Main function in C++ is always written below rest other functions in the end.
#2 the length function has to return an integer of array length. This exact formula works if written outside a function.

👉 Inside a function, arr becomes a pointer, so sizeof(arr) is wrong
👉 This will NOT give correct length
Now how this ,"sizeof (arr)/ sizeof (arr[0])" works ? 

Assume:
int arr[] = {1,2,3,4,5};
1. sizeof(arr)

👉 Total memory used by the array

Each int = 4 bytes
5 elements → 5 × 4 = 20 bytes
sizeof(arr) = 20
2. sizeof(arr[0])

👉 Size of one element

sizeof(arr[0]) = 4
3. Divide them
n = 20 / 4 = 5

👉 Number of elements = 5
🔹 Final Meaning
int n = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(arr[0]);

👉 “Total size of array ÷ size of one element = number of elements”

🔹 Why this works

Because:
Array is stored contiguously in memor & all elements are of same size. 

In interviews, better use:

vector<int> v;
v.size();

Because:
a) safer
b) works everywhere
c) no confusion

👉 In C++:

arrays → no length function
containers (vector, string) → have .size() / .length()

